AB What explains the splintering of the sociological imagination? Why do so
   many rival schools contend for influence? Is there a chance for
   consensus? Donald N. Levine seeks to answer these questions in his
   intriguing recent study of the sociological tradition. He contends that
   sociology has been divided from the start along national lines, yet
   continues to progress towards harmony thanks to the "dialogical"
   commitments of the various national traditions. I argue that Levine
   misjudges the character and depth of past and present rifts, and that he
   overestimates the likelihood of future disciplinary unity.
