AB Within the discipline of sociology, approaches to studying culture have
   shifted markedly over the last forty years. In this article, we review
   these changes as well as Richard Peterson's contributions to the field,
   arguing that his work played a vital role in developing the study of
   culture as a legitimate subject. While studies of culture were marginal
   during sociology's structural period of the 1960, the 'production of
   culture' perspective of the 1970 established the arts as a legitimate
   topic by applying structural analysis to the popular culture industry
