   years. Initially, Peterson introduced the production-of-culture approach
   as a grounded theoretical perspective, rather than a formal theory.
   Theoretically, this perspective was undergirded by assumptions about
   culture as genetic code. From this point of departure, Peterson
   subsequently moved to consider cultural consumption. Specifically, his
   analysis of 'culture classes' and characterization of cultural
   'omnivores' moved beyond narrower structuralist class theories of
   consumption. Given these two strands of cultural analysis-of production
   and consumption-the question arose of how to arrive at an integrated
   theory of relations between the two. A review of the sociologies of
   Wendy Griswold and Howard S. Becker suggests two central issues:
